# Backend Java Spring Boot Standards

## File Naming Conventions

### Controllers
- **Pattern**: `*Controller.java`
- **Example**: `SeatController.java`, `CheckInController.java`
- **Location**: `com.skyhigh.controller`

### Services
- **Interface Pattern**: `*Service.java`
- **Implementation Pattern**: `*ServiceImpl.java`
- **Example**: `SeatService.java`, `SeatServiceImpl.java`
- **Location**: `com.skyhigh.service`

### Repositories
- **Pattern**: `*Repository.java`
- **Example**: `SeatRepository.java`, `PassengerRepository.java`
- **Location**: `com.skyhigh.repository`
- **Type**: Extend `JpaRepository<Entity, ID>`

### Entities
- **Pattern**: `*.java` (singular noun)
- **Example**: `Seat.java`, `Passenger.java`, `CheckIn.java`
- **Location**: `com.skyhigh.entity`

### DTOs (Data Transfer Objects)
- **Request Pattern**: `*Request.java` or `*DTO.java`
- **Response Pattern**: `*Response.java` or `*DTO.java`
- **Example**: `SeatReservationRequest.java`, `CheckInResponse.java`
- **Location**: `com.skyhigh.dto`

### Exceptions
- **Pattern**: `*Exception.java`
- **Example**: `SeatConflictException.java`, `PaymentFailedException.java`
- **Location**: `com.skyhigh.exception`

### Configuration Classes
- **Pattern**: `*Config.java`
- **Example**: `SecurityConfig.java`, `DatabaseConfig.java`
- **Location**: `com.skyhigh.config`

## Spring Boot Best Practices

### Dependency Injection
```java
// ✅ GOOD - Constructor injection
@Service
public class SeatServiceImpl implements SeatService {
    private final SeatRepository seatRepository;
    
    public SeatServiceImpl(SeatRepository seatRepository) {
        this.seatRepository = seatRepository;
    }
}

// ❌ BAD - Field injection
@Service
public class SeatServiceImpl {
    @Autowired
    private SeatRepository seatRepository;
}
```

### Controller Design
```java
// ✅ GOOD
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/v1/flights")
public class SeatController {
    
    @GetMapping("/{flightId}/seat-map")
    public ResponseEntity<SeatMapResponse> getSeatMap(@PathVariable String flightId) {
        // Implementation
    }
}
```

### Exception Handling
- Use `@ControllerAdvice` for global exception handling
- Return proper HTTP status codes (see api-conventions.mdc)
- Include error details in response body

### Transaction Management
```java
// ✅ GOOD - Use @Transactional for operations modifying data
@Service
public class CheckInServiceImpl {
    
    @Transactional
    public CheckIn confirmCheckIn(String checkInId) {
        // Multiple database operations
    }
}
```

## Concurrency Control

**Reference**: See PRD.md Section 5.3 for conflict-free seat assignment requirements

- Use optimistic locking with `@Version` annotation on entities
- Implement proper exception handling for concurrent modifications
- Follow database patterns defined in database-patterns.mdc

## Logging Standards

```java
// ✅ GOOD - Use SLF4J
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;

@Service
public class SeatServiceImpl {
    private static final Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(SeatServiceImpl.class);
    
    public void reserveSeat(String seatId) {
        logger.info("Reserving seat: {}", seatId);
        // Implementation
    }
}
```

**Log Levels**:
- `DEBUG`: Detailed diagnostic information
- `INFO`: Important business events
- `WARN`: Potentially harmful situations
- `ERROR`: Error events that might still allow the application to continue

## Testing Standards

### Test File Naming
- **Unit Tests**: `*Test.java`
- **Integration Tests**: `*IntegrationTest.java`
- **Example**: `SeatServiceTest.java`, `SeatControllerIntegrationTest.java`

### Test Structure
```java
// ✅ GOOD - Clear test naming
@Test
public void reserveSeat_WhenSeatAvailable_ShouldReturnReservation() {
    // Arrange
    // Act
    // Assert
}

@Test
public void reserveSeat_WhenSeatAlreadyHeld_ShouldThrowConflictException() {
    // Test implementation
}
```

### Coverage Requirements
- **Minimum Coverage**: 80%
- **Focus Areas**: Services, controllers, repositories
- **Tools**: JaCoCo for coverage reporting

### Test Annotations
- `@SpringBootTest` for integration tests
- `@WebMvcTest` for controller tests
- `@DataJpaTest` for repository tests
- `@MockBean` for mocking dependencies

## Security Patterns

**Reference**: See PRD.md Section 11 for security requirements

### Authentication
- Implement JWT-based authentication
- Use Spring Security for endpoint protection
- Store tokens securely, never in logs

### Authorization
```java
// ✅ GOOD - Role-based access control
@PreAuthorize("hasRole('PASSENGER')")
@PostMapping("/check-ins/{checkInId}/confirm")
public ResponseEntity<CheckInResponse> confirmCheckIn() {
    // Implementation
}
```

### Audit Logging
- Log all state transitions (seat reservations, check-ins)
- Include user ID, timestamp, and action in audit logs
- Never log sensitive data (passwords, payment tokens)

### Rate Limiting
- Implement rate limiting for public endpoints
- Use Redis for distributed rate limiting
- Return HTTP 429 when limits exceeded

## Code Quality

- Follow standard Java naming conventions (camelCase for methods/variables, PascalCase for classes)
- Keep methods focused and under 50 lines
- Use meaningful variable names
- Document complex business logic with comments
- Run linter/formatter before committing
